[Whirling disease is caused by the protozoan parasite _Myxobolus
cerebralis_. It poses no known health hazard to humans who handle or
consume fish, nor to any animal other than fish. It has a 2-stage life
cycle involving trout or salmon and aquatic Tubifex worms. When fish eat
infected worms or ingest the spores they release, the parasite attacks the
head and gills, damaging the cartilage surrounding the brain. This causes
CNS damage leading to erratic swimming, tail-chasing, and whirling. It is
not always fatal. On death, spores are released and are ingested by the
Tubifex. Birds or predatory fish that eat infected fish or worms
contribute to the spread. - Mod.TG]
